00:00:55.840 --> 00:01:02.959
a file, such as a folder, right? It could be also a regular cloud storage, or even SharePoint,

00:01:03.919 --> 00:01:10.080
or especially POSIT Connect, where you can not only publish tiny apps or dash apps, you can also

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:18.559
publish pins. And lastly, we have a Databricks volume, which is basically a database of

00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:26.639
which is what we just recently added as a backend to the pins package. So the idea here would be

00:01:26.639 --> 00:01:36.320
that as a user or a developer, you can write a pin into the board that then can be used downstream,

00:01:37.279 --> 00:01:40.879
either by yourself and other projects, or maybe other members of your team,

00:01:41.519 --> 00:01:49.040
or maybe even apps can read the pin and use them. So why do I want to use a pin, right?

00:01:50.959 --> 00:01:59.040
I could use easily, you know, a shared drive that the team has access to. Well, pins themselves

00:01:59.599 --> 00:02:05.040
automatically are version, which I think is really cool because you can access the versions of those

00:02:05.040 --> 00:02:12.720
pins programmatically. And they also allow you to be able to go back in case there's some mistakes

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:18.720
that you need to fix, or even help with reproducibility. You can also customize the

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:24.639
