00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:12.880
I wanted to mention this real quickly because we had a customer asking about this, about

00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:18.479
when to use a database versus using a pin. The main thing that I think you have to

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:24.960
keep in mind is that whenever you want to decide that, you have to think in terms of

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:31.679
how big is your data, right? And how much of that data are you using? Because if at the time that

00:03:31.679 --> 00:03:36.479
you're going to do your analysis, you're going to use part of the data, then it's better if you use

00:03:36.479 --> 00:03:41.759
a database because you can query the data to download the portion of the data that you need

00:03:41.759 --> 00:03:48.080
and then using whatever analysis. Because with the pin, when you say pin read, for example,

00:03:48.080 --> 00:03:53.520
it downloads the entire data set. So if the data is really big, it may not be feasible

00:03:53.919 --> 00:03:58.080
to download it every time if you're not going to use the whole thing.

00:03:58.960 --> 00:04:03.039
So that's the main thing that you have to keep in mind. I would say to think in terms of

00:04:03.919 --> 00:04:11.600
the pins is another tool in your toolbox rather than a replacement of something such as a database.

