00:13:52.400 --> 00:14:01.280
trigger that prediction using Spark Apply through Sparkly R. So it's really cool how this works

00:14:01.280 --> 00:14:08.239
because it allows us to do one thing that it sets it apart from the regular way that we serve

00:14:08.960 --> 00:14:16.479
models, right? Whenever you serve a model, you generally what are doing is serving it as a REST

00:14:16.479 --> 00:14:26.559
API endpoint. So a typical self model would require that you send it whatever set of data

00:14:27.280 --> 00:14:33.200
and then it would return a prediction, right? So let's say we have a table that has a million

00:14:33.200 --> 00:14:40.799
records. If you were to use the traditional model, then you would then have to do a million calls

00:14:40.799 --> 00:14:46.239
in order to score the entire dataset. That of course is totally acceptable today, we do that

00:14:46.239 --> 00:14:53.599
all day long. But what I'm proposing is that we do this a little bit differently. So the idea is

00:14:53.599 --> 00:15:02.000
that Spark can read the data and by default Spark partitions the data into smaller sections.

00:15:03.520 --> 00:15:10.559
Then because it allows us to run RUDS or meaning that you can run R code inside Spark,

00:15:10.559 --> 00:15:18.640
you can have a small program that will then read the volume, meaning the model from the volume,

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:24.479
and it will run the predictions in each of these segments or partitions

00:15:25.119 --> 00:15:33.840
individually and also in parallel. So that way, instead of querying the model a million times,

00:15:33.840 --> 00:15:39.280
you're querying it as many partitions as there are. There may be tens, maybe even a hundred,

00:15:39.280 --> 00:15:45.520
depends on how big your data is and how much Spark partitions it. But it's much more efficient

00:15:45.520 --> 00:15:51.760
and definitely faster. So that's why I think this is a very good model to consider.

